            <p>M M. Sollas Esqr<lb/>
                Phila 12 Dec 1861<lb/>
                Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I deem it an honor to have been called<lb/> upon to solve a question which has already been<lb/> propounded to Jewish Ministers of distinction&#44; but reasons<lb/> that I need not explain prompt me to offer my opinion<lb/> privately instead of giving it publicity.<lb/></p>
            <p>I have carefully read your communication to Dr Raphall&#44;<lb/> wherein the merits of the case in which you are interested<lb/> are fully discussed&#44; and I do not hesitate to say that<lb/> the conduct of the wardens of your congregation is alike<lb/> unwarrantable and blamable.  According to the laws<lb/> by which Israelites are graded&#44; a child of a Hebrew woman&#44;<lb/> though born of a Gentile&#44; is considered as one of our people<lb/> in every respect&#44; with the sole exception that a female<lb/> of such an extraction&#44; is not allowed to marry a priest<lb/> &#40;Cohen&#41;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>so it is explicitly laid down in the &#91;&#63;&#93; N&#91;&#63;&#93; vol<lb/> Eben A&#91;&#63;&#93; sect 4 par 5 &#38; 15 on the authority of the<lb/> Talmud treatise Yebamot p 45 p 2.<lb/></p>
            <p>Mr Bessun is not therefore to be regarded as a proselyte<lb/> but as a native Jew&#44; whom&#44; certain circumstances which<lb/> he could not control&#44; prevented his entering the covenant<lb/> of Abraham at its due time&#44; but who with commendable<lb/> zeal submitted himself to the performance of that observance<lb/> in later years.  He is consequently entitled to all privileges<lb/> connected with synagogual worship&#44; and whosoever denies<lb/> the same to him&#44; is greatly to be reprehended.<lb/></p>
            <p>The Revd Max Wolf acted on the premises as it behooves<lb/> every pious man&#59; and far from deserving censure&#44;<lb/> he must claim our thanks for having spiritually<lb/> <sic>benefitted</sic> <del>his</del> a fellow believer.  Besides&#44; it happens<lb/> that I am personally acquainted with that Gentle&#45;<lb/>man&#44; so that I may freely state that he is too<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>much of a scholar to misunderstand the law&#44; and too<lb/> honest to act in <sic>contraviction</sic> thereof.<lb/></p>
            <p>I trust that the pending question will be settled ami&#45;<lb/>&#45;cably&#44; and I can assure you&#44; dear sir&#44; that to learn<lb/> that the congregation have retracted&#44; and Mr<lb/> Bessun is permitted to worship the God of Israel in their midst&#44;<lb/> will much gratify<lb/></p>
            <p>yours respectfully<lb/>
                S Morais<lb/>
            </p>
            
        </body>
